FROGS 5 WRITING GUIDE
For anyone -- human or AI -- writing prose for any FROGS 5 campaign.
Read this before you write read-aloud text, in-world documents, or NPC dialogue.

The principles and examples in sections I-IV and VI are project-agnostic; use them anywhere.
Section V is one worked example drawn from Torygg's Legacy. Plain text; "--" stands in for an
em-dash. (In Torygg's Legacy these rules are also summarized in AI_README section X.)

=======================================================
I. THE ONE PRINCIPLE: EVERY WORD IS STRUCTURAL
=======================================================

Maximum detail, minimum words. These do not conflict, because detail is information and
filler is length wearing information's clothes.

A word earns its place by changing the meaning of the sentence. The test is the cut: remove
the word, and if the meaning holds, the word was doing no work -- leave it cut. Filler is not
neutral. It buries the picture it claims to paint and inflates length with nothing.

Each sentence builds on the one before it. The reader is assembling a mental model as they
go; every sentence either adds to that model or muddies it. You earn a subversion only by
first constructing the thing you subvert.

Everything in sections II-V follows from this principle. They are the specific ways prose
breaks it.

=======================================================
II. THE HARD BANS
=======================================================

--- 1. NEVER WRITE A PLAYER CHARACTER'S ACTIONS, CHOICES, OR REALIZATIONS ---

Discovery belongs to the players at the table. Prep that makes a PC solve, read, deduce, or
speak a discovery steals the reveal and the agency, and it feels terrible to the player whose
character was just driven without them. We are capable writers; we never need this crutch.

Write what is PRESENT (the object, the text, the evidence). Put what it MEANS in a separate
GM-only block. Hand the players the thing; let them drive. A PC's expertise is an opening the
GM offers live -- never a conclusion prep dictates.

  BEFORE: She picks the lock, steps inside, and realizes the place was abandoned in a hurry.
  AFTER:  The lock gives on the second pin. Inside, two drawers hang open and a chair lies on
          its side; a half-packed satchel sits on the bed. [GM-only: someone left in a hurry.
          Let the players read the room and say so; do not say it for them.]

--- 2. "COLD" IS BANNED AS TEXTURE; SO ARE MOOD-WORDS USED AS FILLER ---

"Cold" gets pasted onto everything -- the lid, the fire, the hate, the love. When everything
is cold, the word means nothing and does no descriptive work. Watch the same way for "wrong,"
"ancient," "eerie," "dread," "a presence," "an absence," "something radiates/pulses." These
name a mood instead of building one.

And the damage outlasts the sentence. A texture word is read as fact and recorded as canon;
later beats must then honor it or fight it. A "cold" dropped in for atmosphere becomes a
constraint the next writer trips over -- a contradiction manufactured out of a word that was
describing nothing. Filler is not inert. It hardens into false canon and costs you downstream.

Earn the mood with one concrete, physical, specific detail.

  BEFORE: The table is wrong somehow. A cold dread hangs over the cold remains of a meal.
  AFTER:  Four chairs are pushed back from the table, and the bread on the plates has gone
          green and hard.

--- 3. DESCRIBE WHAT IS THERE; NEVER DESCRIBE BY WHAT ISN'T ---

Subtractive negation injects context into the reader's model and then makes them delete it a
breath later -- errant detail raised only to be discarded. It guarantees confusion and burns
the reader's attention for nothing.

State the positive fact.

  BEFORE: The door wasn't forced. It was opened from the inside. No marks, no damage.
  AFTER:  The door stands open, the bar lifted clear and leaned against the wall beside it.

(There is one legitimate use of negation -- see section III.)

--- 4. DO NOT INVENT CONNECTIONS THE STRUCTURE DOESN'T SUPPORT ---

When two factions, threats, or plot threads are established as separate, do not link, contrast,
or echo them to manufacture resonance. A character should not "brace" for one enemy inside
another's content. Invented cross-connections break established canon and confuse players who
are tracking those threads as distinct. If a connection is not already in the structure, it
does not exist. (E.g., in Torygg's Legacy the Dragon Cult and the Dagon corruption are
separate enemies -- never tie them together.)

--- 5. NO OMNISCIENCE; DESCRIBE IN THE ORDER THINGS ARE PERCEIVED ---

Writers reflexively hand characters and readers knowledge no one present could have -- duration,
history, an actor's intent, the meaning of a thing rather than its appearance. They also
describe out of sequence, reaching back to narrate a moment already passed. Both yank the
reader off their feet.

Only what is observable right now belongs in the read-aloud. Conclusions about history or
intent belong in the GM-only note, drawn by the players if at all. And describe events in the
order the characters meet them: if the text is read once the party is inside a room, do not
narrate what they felt on the way in.

  BEFORE: The heat hits you before you reach the door. The lamps have burned untended for a
          century, and you know at once the owner left in no hurry.
  AFTER:  The room is warm. The lamps burn straight and even. [GM-only: they have burned
          untended for a century and the owner left unhurried -- let the players infer the
          calm from the order of the place; state neither outright.]

(Related: voice is a TELL. Keep an in-world document true to its writer; a private log should
never explain things to an outsider for the reader's benefit.)

=======================================================
III. THE ONE LEGITIMATE NEGATION: ADDITIVE, NOT SUBTRACTIVE
=======================================================

"Not just X -- Y" works only when X is true, STAYS true, and Y stacks a deeper layer on top
of it. The reader keeps both.

  GOOD: "Not just filler, it is structural waste." Filler is real; waste is the truth built
        above it. Both words do work, and the sentence escalates. This CONSTRUCTS the thing.

The banned version asserts X only to erase it ("not cold, but ..."). That is destruction:
it builds an understanding and then demands the reader tear it down.

THE TEST: does the negated clause survive as true and get built on? Keep it. Is it raised
only to be knocked down? Cut it and state the real thing alone. Most negation fails this
test; default to stating Y by itself.

=======================================================
IV. CALIBRATION (the GM's stated preferences)
=======================================================

- READ-ALOUD AND IN-WORLD DOCS carry the strict standard. Mechanical text (stat blocks, GM
  directions) may stay terse shorthand, held to clarity rather than cadence.
- GM READ-OUTS STAY. Keep the read-aloud clean; put interpretation in a separate GM-only
  block ("What this establishes"). The GM wants the facts fast and the prose uncluttered.
- EARNED LYRICISM IS WELCOME. Figurative language and longer cadence are good wherever each
  one carries something a plain sentence cannot. The economy rule still governs: a simile
  that decorates is filler; a simile that conveys is structure.
- EMOTION: lead with the concrete fact, then add a short GM-only cue for the intended feeling
  and delivery. Show the evidence first; the one-line tone note rides underneath it.

=======================================================
V. WORKED EXAMPLE: AN EMPTY THRONE (from Torygg's Legacy)
=======================================================

The party reaches the chamber a powerful enemy woke in and walked out of. He is gone; they
read him off what he left. The goal is to make them feel his strength, his patience, and his
intent -- through present, observable evidence, with no one in the room.

THE BEFORE (breaks rules 2, 3, and 5):
  "The lid is thrown aside -- not lifted, THROWN, cracked against the dais by something that
   did not need leverage. The cold here is not the ward's clean absence. It is the cold of
   something that lay in the dark hating, with perfect patience, for four thousand years. The
   braziers have stayed lit, and the heat reaches you before the doorway does. A line of
   footprints crosses to the door -- the walk of a man crossing a room he owns -- and you are
   certain that whatever rose from this box already knows you came."

What's wrong:
  - Rule 2: "cold" three times, carrying nothing; "hating" names a mood the prose never shows.
  - Rule 3: "not lifted, THROWN," "did not need leverage," "not the ward's clean absence" all
    describe by negation.
  - Rule 5: "have stayed lit" (how do they know the duration?), "four thousand years" (same),
    "the walk of a man crossing a room he owns" (an inference no one could read off footprints),
    "already knows you came" (flat omniscience). "The heat reaches you before the doorway" is
    out of sequence -- this is read once they are inside.

THE AFTER (shows the same three things through what the eye reports, in order):
  "The room is warm -- warm the way a forge stays warm hours after the smith has gone home.
   The braziers burn straight and white over a floor swept clean. The sarcophagus stands open
   at the center, its lid leaned against the dais: a slab of stone two hands thick, split
   across the middle. A handprint is sunk into the underside, the fingers driven to the second
   knuckle, the stone dimpled around them as though it had gone soft as tallow under the hand.
   The dust inside the box holds a shape -- tall, on its back, arms folded, a mask over the
   face, whole to the shoulders and broken there, where it sat up. From the foot of the dais a
   line of footprints crosses the swept floor to the door, evenly spaced, each stride the
   length of the last."
  WHAT THIS ESTABLISHES (GM-only, for the GM to hold and the players to earn):
  - The warmth, the lit braziers, the swept floor: the chamber is kept and recently used.
  - The handprint on the lid's underside, fingers to the second knuckle: it pushed the lid off
    from inside with one hand, hard enough to dent stone. Strength past mortal scale.
  - The undisturbed dust holding a whole body: it lay still for an age, then rose.
  - The even, unhurried, evenly-spaced footprints to the door: it left at a walk, in no hurry,
    with somewhere to be -- the bearing of something that owns the room.
  - Deliver quiet. This is the first room a true villain occupied; the party becomes people it
    will remember. Lead with the warmth and the handprint.

Why the AFTER works: every claim is something a person standing in the room can see -- the
warmth, the print, the dust, the spacing of the prints. The conclusions the BEFORE stated
outright (strength, patience, ownership, "he knows you came") moved into the GM-only note,
where the players reach them or do not. It runs in order, all in the room, with no reach back
to the approach. The forge simile stays because it carries a fact a plain word would miss --
heat lingering from a source now gone; its old trailing clause ("the heat still pushing off
the walls") was cut, because the simile already said it.

=======================================================
VI. THE SELF-CHECK PASS (run over every draft before it ships)
=======================================================

1. CUT-TEST. Remove each word and clause in turn. If the meaning holds, leave it cut.
2. NEGATION. For every "not X": does X stay true and get built on? If it is raised only to be
   deleted, cut it and state the real thing.
3. PC AGENCY. Did I make a player character solve, read, realize, decide, or speak a
   discovery? Convert it to present evidence plus a GM-only note on the meaning.
4. MOOD-WORDS. Search for cold / wrong / ancient / eerie / dread / absence / presence /
   "something." Replace each with a concrete detail or cut it.
5. CONNECTIONS. Did I link two threads the structure keeps separate? Cut it.
6. OMNISCIENCE. Did I state anything the characters present cannot perceive -- duration,
   history, an actor's intent? Move it to the GM-only note. Is the description in the order
   the characters meet it? Reorder to match.
7. SHOW, DON'T INSTRUCT. The read-aloud shows; the feeling and the meaning live in the
   GM-only note beneath it.
